Since Michael has to deal with the for loop for each listener I had him make the call:

When I look at the common use case of how customers will use Octavia, it seems that most day-to-day operations are going to be at a listener level because of the decision to have one HAProxy process per listener.  Examples: Adding/Deleting ports, changing the members of the pool, changing health monitors, etc.  By doing this at the listener level it limits the downtime on the other listeners that are part of the load balancer and reduces the amount of data we are pushing out to the Amphora.  This could be done with logic on the agent that looks for configuration changes, but that is added logic that could be error prone and we would still be using more network bandwidth.

Defining the APIs at the load balancer level is better for recovery of a large number of failed Amphorae and fits the model where a load balancer is equivalent to one HAProxy process (i.e. stacking listeners).  It also exposes the shared fate that a load balancer truly has around the IP.  I.e. if listener A and listener B share an IP address and listener B fails to build for some reason, you have to fail listener A and attempt to rebuild both to move the load balancer to a new Amphora.

Basically, I think exposing the listener level in the API optimizes for the \x9dhappy\x9d case and this is why I am ok with it.  

I think in later versions we would likely wish to come back and allow/optimize for listener stacking, but that is a different issue.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-24 20:06:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

[{'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2014-09-25 15:54:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-09-25 16:47:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

The host filter is not needed. If we already know which host should be handling the request, the request should be sent to the host directly. The scheduler doesn't need to be involved in this case."}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2014-09-25 17:14:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Xing,

We should use scheduler anyway, at least for one reason:

there could be not enough space on host and scheduler will normally handle it using capacityFilter.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-09-25 17:20:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Valeriy,

The shares table is the only one that has a "host" field. The snapshots table doesn't have a "host" field.  The snapshot is always handled by the same "host" which manages the source share. So if it is out of space, creation will fail.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-09-25 17:22:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

In your patch, if snapshot is used, only one host is passed. So there's no more than 1 host anyway."}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2014-09-25 17:23:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

It should be handled properly - by CapacityFilter.'}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2014-09-25 17:24:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

1 or 0 + other filters make it 1 or 0.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-09-25 17:28:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

API sends request to the scheduler. Scheduler chooses a host and sends request to that host. If you already know which host to send request to, the request should be sent to the host directly, without scheduler in the middle. It is an extra unnecessary step.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-09-25 17:30:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This is how Cinder handles it when the API already knows which host should receive the request: 

https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/master/cinder/volume/flows/api/create_volume.py#L732'}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2014-09-25 17:51:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Then it should be fixed there.

Scheduler can be last point of share creation attempt, without bothering manila-share host.

So, if we have two possible results ("no hosts" and "this host"), then scheduling should be used.

Also, there are possible case for generic driver backends:

If more than one backends are used and all of them with generic driver onboard, then we can disable "HostFilter" and successfully create shares from snapshots on any host. Your proposal does not allow it.'}, {'account_id': 11878, 'date': '2014-09-25 17:53:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Agree with xing. There is an unnecessary overhead of making a call to the scheduler. A direct request to the host should be made.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-25 18:35:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Take a look at /opt/stack/manila/bin/manila-share:

Line 55
host = "%s@%s" % (CONF.host, backend)

When manila-share is started, the host is actually host@backend. This host info will be stored in the "host" field in the shares table after a share is created.

When you pass the filter_properties to the scheduler with the host info, it already has backend name in it. So it will not have more than 1 backend. 

filter_properties.update({'host': snapshot['share']['host']})'}, {'account_id': 7534, 'date': '2014-09-26 08:58:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

[{'created': '2014-09-25 15:54:03.000000000', 'message': "Add HostFilter to be able to use specific host

If we try create share from snapshot, source host is not chosen for sure.
In case we have multibackend installation, other hosts won't be filtered
and error will be raised.

As solution for it HostFilter is added:
- enabled by default
- if snapshot used, - only one host passed or nothing
- if snapshot not used, - all hosts are passed

To make your current installation work with this change, you should do:
- apply this change
- update file manila.egg-info/entry_points.txt as setup.cfg updated
- restart manila-scheduler

Change-Id: I0743c92b55e123409133ea623e0f8ec03d8e9aaa
Closes-Bug: #1373882

commit_message:
Fix creation of share from snapshot

Current behaviour does not take into accout source host of snapshot for
share creation from snapshot. It leads to impossibility to create share
if improper host was scheduled using multibackend setup.

Solution:
Implement config opt that allows us call required host directly without
scheduling in case we have host restriction and allow scheduling in case
we don't. We do not have such restricion, for example, using multibackend
installation with generic drivers onboard.

Change-Id: I0743c92b55e123409133ea623e0f8ec03d8e9aaa
Closes-Bug: #1373882

Thanks for keeping an eye out on these OpenStack common libraries Noorul.

While I was comparing openstack-common.conf with solumclient/openstack/common/* I noticed that there are modules within that directory, such as gettextutils, importutils, etc. which are not listed in openstack-common.conf. Why is that? Shouldn't openstack-common.conf list all the modules?

Second, I am curious to know how is openstack-common.conf used within our code?

Otherwise LGTM."}, {'account_id': 8334, 'date': '2014-09-24 15:50:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

This is because they are dependent modules for the modules that we need.'}, {'account_id': 8334, 'date': '2014-09-24 15:51:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

About Oslo, it is very well documented here.

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Oslo

If you have anything specific after reading that, let me know.'}, {'account_id': 2506, 'date': '2014-09-25 21:24:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Noorul,

Thanks for sharing the link. It is very informative.

In the "Why aren't alpha releases of oslo.config published to PyPI?" section there is this comment:

"The best solution we've come up with to date is to publish oslo.config pre-releases (aka alphas) using the X.Y.ZaN numbering scheme to tarballs.openstack.org and reference them in requirements.txt using: 

-f http://tarballs.openstack.org/oslo.config/oslo.config-1.2.0a3.tar.gz#egg=oslo.config-1.2.0a3
oslo.config>=1.2.0a3 "

Is it saying that instead of copying over the oslo library code and maintaining it in our repositories, we could use such a tarballed version of the library, albeit some previous version, in our code?

If so, any reason why we should not follow that approach?'}, {'account_id': 8334, 'date': '2014-09-26 01:17:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

What they meant is that, if someone has to use alpha release they have to use tar ball. This is relevant only for non opensrack projects. I think our pypi mirrors will have alpha relases. Also this is specifically for individual packages. What we are keeping in our repo is code that are not factored out to separate packages. If you see this patch, we are actually removing test module and use oslo.test package as this is a new package. Similarly as and when they create new packages from common code we can remove them and switch over.'}, {'account_id': 2506, 'date': '2014-09-26 18:27:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Thanks Noorul for the clarification. Makes sense.

I have one last follow up question.
How did you find out that

solumclient/openstack/common/test.py

is now replaced by base.py from oslotest.'}, {'account_id': 8334, 'date': '2014-09-26 22:27:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

I came to know from Angus's patch in solum. But I also remember reading about oslotest in dev mailing list.

But to know whether something is changig in os/common we should closely watch."}, {'account_id': 2506, 'date': '2014-09-26 22:36:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

Ok then.. here you go.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-26 22:39:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: -Verified

commit_message:
Remove db_enforce_mysql_charset option for db_sync of glance-manage

This is a deprecated option only should be used for migration. As we
scheduled before, now glance removes it out from Juno release.

Change-Id: Ice4ade659307ee5e635a75d6637b4664ee431c20
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

[{'created': '2014-09-25 21:42:31.000000000', 'message': 'VMware store: Use the Content-Length if available

Change I579084460e7f61ab4042632d17ec0f045fa6f5af changed the VMware
store to use chunked encoding to upload data to the underlying backend.
We should do that only if the image size is not provided or zero and not
all the time.
This patch addressed the issue by checking the image_size before upload.

Merged in Glance: Change-Id: If348be7fd24fd05146b0c86bef45b79f600cc0f7
Closes-Bug: #1336970

Change-Id: I58efc8981b38d1e445f9acde669802b97e4b2077
'}]
commit_message:
VMware store: Use the Content-Length if available

Change I579084460e7f61ab4042632d17ec0f045fa6f5af changed the VMware
store to use chunked encoding to upload data to the underlying backend.
We should do that only if the image size is not provided or zero and not
all the time.
This patch addressed the issue by checking the image_size before upload.

Merged in Glance: Change-Id: If348be7fd24fd05146b0c86bef45b79f600cc0f7
Closes-Bug: #1336970

Change-Id: I58efc8981b38d1e445f9acde669802b97e4b2077

[{'created': '2014-09-07 14:35:44.000000000', 'message': 'Test formatting errors with log level being emitted

The test to ensure that formatting errors are handled properly was being
run using info level logging, but the default log configuration for
tests does not emit messages at that level, so switch to error.

commit_message:
Test formatting errors with log level being emitted

The test to ensure that formatting errors are handled properly was being
run using info level logging, but the default log configuration for
tests does not emit messages at that level, so switch to error.

Change-Id: Ie11a51deea65627b45a11d7dfca36d16c1b5949e

commit_message:
Make rbd store's pool handling more universal

Currently we ignore the pool part of the location throughout the rbd store code.
If there is a pool specified, use that. Otherwise we can still fall back to the
configured pool.

This is a required change if we want to support ephemeral disk snapshotting later on
as in that scenario the ephemeral pool might be a different pool from images pool,
yet we're going to need to reference the snapshot of a disk in the ephemeral pool.

Change-Id: Ie415667a809975948c8cfb71ec63a0905995fa67
Closes-Bug: 1368128

commit_message:
Update /etc/cinder/cinder.conf.sample for memcache

It appears that an update to keystone middleware earlier today
added options for memcache_secret_key, memcache_pool_dead_retry,
memcache_pool_maxsize, memcache_pool_socket_timeout,
memcache_pool_unused_timeout, memcache_pool_conn_get_timeout and
memcache_use_advanced_pool.  The commit that added these options
was: a7beb50b38be5c3dd4c44d68ad79d1bb206dab6b - "Add an optional
advanced pool of memcached clients".

This has once again caused the check_uptodate.sh script to fail.

This patch updates cinder.sample.conf .

Change-Id: Ibcf19ccc81a56a9a3e795022e3e07bc061fa9401
Closes-bug: 1374154

commit_message:
Declare cinder::glance to set glance_api_version

Prior to syncing upstream cinder module, glance_api_version was set from
cinder::backend::rbd. New upstream moved this to cinder::glance.

Change-Id: Ied9f4308b998e9f345449e03a00221de41261e85
Closes-Bug: #1373096

commit_message:
Not able to delete a pseudo-folder via horizon

Through horizon the user not able to delete a
pseudo-folder. it giving a error message like
'you are not allowed to delete object'

problem-1:
'subfolders' datatype is not added in the
allowed datatypes tuple, so the delete operation
is not allowed for pseudo-folder. now the 'subfolder'
is added in the tuple.

problem-2:
the object name is starting with container name and
not trailing with '/'. now the object name is modified
before sending to swift client.(removing the container
name and trailing with '/'.

Change-Id: Ifced62b24a9b6e4800b70dae2912ff16d809743d
Closes-Bug: #1317016
Co-Authored-By: Mizielski Robert <robert.mizielski@cloudwatt.com>
(cherry picked from commit a46ce9e3ffaa4ee18618ea18496a76508717c871)

commit_message:
Replace start_guests with resume_guests

Fuel UI offers an option to "start guests on reboot" which,
if set to true, will attempt to restart all guests on a
given host regardless of prior status. This commit changes
the nova.conf entry from start_guests_on_boot to
resume_guets_state_on_host_boot.

Change-Id: I3515c6350c1314cf091480ea109c8ade6195ea17
Partial-Bug: #1352284

commit_message:
Proper port for LBaaS members

This patch set makes loadbalancer select a port on pool subnet
for new members if possible.

Conflicts:
        openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/loadbalancers/tests.py
        openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/loadbalancers/workflows.py

Closes-Bug: #1288859

Change-Id: I0809908ec5d15a448691dccf526b66308cf929d4

commit_message:
Use default_project_id as user project for keystone v3

This fixes the keystone api module so that it looks for the
default_project_id attribute on the user and uses that as the
primary project.

Closes-Bug: 1347840
Change-Id: If3ea4625ae50ae4561df3e566d1236b86226307b
(cherry picked from commit 03f9caa9d1e43ac4c4db4c10c16e07ca14daaf6e)

commit_message:
Fix _parse_datetime in simple tenant usage extension

_parse_datetime in os-simple-tenant-usage incorrectly attempts
to parse the datetime string even when it is None. As a result
a 400 BadRequest is returned. This has the overall effect of making
the start and end datetime parameters compulsory when they are meant
to be optional.

Note that this restores the behavior where start/end are optional which is
in contradiction to the API docs, but is the long standing API behaviour.
This was an API change which was accidentally applied in commit
I8e0e870727d687da165c809ffb7a4456bff81122 as part of some nova internal
changes but not picked up by the unitests

Change-Id: I00427379dc7aa39770f9a16ff026addb6e311735
Closes-Bug: 1300972

commit_message:
Avoid traceback logs from simple tenant usage extension

Avoid generating traceback logs when invalid formatted datetime
parameters are passed to the simple tenant usage
extension. Exceptions have not been correctly handled by the
os-simple-tenant usage extension which results in tracebacks
being output to the log files. This patch correctly handles
exceptions as a result of badly formatted datetime strings.

Conflicts:
        nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/contrib/test_simple_tenant_usage.py

Change-Id: Iecd42239357b96450b6530c0486b27c68995c37f
Partial-Bug: 1300972
(cherry picked from commit f60c72fac04a97b321a7f2bd0865c1ae81250882)

commit_message:
Allow admin_bind_host to be settable in the keystone.conf

Change server recipe and template to allow the admin_bind_host
to be set to the identity_admin endpoint defined in Common.

Change-Id: I1043d8e9137ea2a6c8f84ee3a2da4f98e3c82521
Closes-Bug: #1368282

commit_message:
Separate endpoints for vncserver_listen and vncserver_proxyclient_address

* define new endpoint for proxy based on existing vnc endpoint
* will be used in Compute  nova-common recipe for nova.conf

Change-Id: I89298db2461b59ab8038dfc01d42f0eb69a8b58c
Partial-Bug: #1367807

commit_message:
Do not lookup l3-agent for floating IP if host=None, dvr issue

If a floating IP has been associated with a port, but the port
has not been associated with an instance, attempting to lookup
the l3-agent hosting it will cause an AgentNotFoundByTypeHost
exception.  Just skip it and go onto the next one.

Change-Id: If3df9770fa9e2d2eada932ee5f243d3458bf7261
Closes-Bug: #1370795

commit_message:
Fix metadata constriant for Common

A patch went in that needed attributes in Common and the ops-messaging
metadata was change to ~> 10.0.1 which worked until Common
was recently bumped to 10.1.  The metadata for Common should have had
a minor version bump, not a patch bump for the new attributes.

Change-Id: I6429d8f770b79ab099c9af5110fe49c88e74bfa0
Closes-Bug: #1373483

commit_message:
Replace misleading max_message_size option name

The max_message_size option name is misleading. The option
determines max size of message post body. Replacing the
option name to max_messages_post_size.

Change-Id: Ie01cee026e7ebf530cdb2709e2c17d030ad95480
Closes-Bug: #1357397

commit_message:
Add sensitive flag to key and certificate resources

Use to ensure that sensitive resource data is not logged by the chef-client.
Need to update Foodcritic to 4.0 to handle new sensitive attribute.

Change-Id: I72c5555750530b15812ef68d6c731ad18931fda0
Closes-Bug: #1371794

commit_message:
Disabling check-requirements job from GBP project

We will need to use some experimental dependencies which are
not part of global requirements. So we need to disable
the check-requirements jobs.

Closes-Bug: #1374263

Change-Id: Ia7c003e124791a15265c125fd8614d086d154ec3

messages: [{'account_id': 10281, 'date': '2014-09-11 18:44:46.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 11197, 'date': '2014-09-11 18:53:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-11 19:18:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1 Build succeeded. - gate-openstack-planet-unittest http://logs.openstack.org/78/120878/1/check/gate-openstack-planet-unittest/2b05ddd : SUCCESS in 20s'}, {'account_id': 287, 'date': '2014-09-11 22:11:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1 the url doesn't seem to be neither an ATOM nor RSS xml feed. I checked that page and didn't found any syndication feed. Can you please check if your blogging platform has one? Also, I noticed that the content of the cloud blog contains openstack-related posts mixed with non-openstack material. I can see how http://www.symantec.com/connect/blogs/configuring-redis-high-availability might be useful for OpenStack, too but the post has no mention of OpenStack so I cannot judge. Most blogging platforms have a way to export feeds (atom or rss) of specific tags or categories. Can you create a category or tag for openstack? In order to merge this patch, you should provide then: an rss or atom feed of content that is strictly about openstack."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-15 20:07:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1 Merge Failed. commit_message:
Don't have more workers than cpus by default

This commit changes the default behavior for starting WSGIServices
to only use the number of cpus on the system. Previously, by default
it would launch N workers for each enabled api where N is the number
of CPUs on the system. If there are 3 enabled APIs this would result
in workers for 3x the number of CPUs being started. This commit
changes the default behavior to launch only N / A where N is the
number of CPUs and A is the number of enabled APIs.

This issue was noticed because occasionally during gate runs we were
seeing oom-killer being invoked. In those instances nova-api is among
the top consumers of memory and with 24 workers we were pushing the
limits of our gate slaves with 8 CPUs and 8GB of RAM.

DocImpact
Partial-Bug: #1366931
Partial-Bug: #1362347
Change-Id: I6803bdf5de59ab3f3c495de2876ea11fffcff6ee

DevStack change I36fe56c063ca921131ad98439bd452cb135916ac introduced
support for https. This requires us to explicitly set the glance
service protocol in redstack for image uploads to work correctly.
Set GLANCE_SERVICE_PROTOCOL to be http (default), which can be

Change-Id: I687486b04939f42f4d9a89da3716e7168f278e8a
Closes-bug: 1374555
'}]
commit_message:
Add GLANCE_SERVICE_PROTOCOL to fix image upload

DevStack change I36fe56c063ca921131ad98439bd452cb135916ac introduced
support for https. This requires us to explicitly set the glance
service protocol in redstack for image uploads to work correctly.
Set GLANCE_SERVICE_PROTOCOL to be http (default), which can be
overridden by setting the environment variable appropriately.

Change-Id: I687486b04939f42f4d9a89da3716e7168f278e8a
Closes-bug: 1374555

commit_message:
Fix endpoint error when running keystone on apache

When running keystone in httpd, horizon could not generate the
right keystone endpoint url. Fixes this issue by retrieving the
whole path from the service_catalog or OPENSTACK_KEYSTONE_URL
and generating a new url.

Change-Id: Id8459947498127e47700d9f690d4ed4d5cadbba9
Closes-bug: #1295128
(cherry picked from commit 48a0d07e45bac04393978776c63b67cd7c71415d)

commit_message:
Refactor ramdisk element to allow alternate implementations

In preparation for enabling Dracut-based ramdisks, this change
factors out functionality that is common to both busybox and Dracut
ramdisks.  Said functionality is moved to a ramdisk-base element
which is added as a dependency of the ramdisk element.  ramdisk now
only contains the functionality specific to building busybox-based
ramdisks.

bp tripleo-juno-dracut-ramdisks
Change-Id: Iad2907c8be491c88727d87ed5e5a720e5beb66c3

commit_message:
Serialization of neutron attrs depends on environment version

It is a quick 'dirty' fix for the issue.
Versioning of serializer must be introduced to avoid such bugs in future.

Closes-Bug: #1362659

Change-Id: Ie25221a6125654bac1810aca4c1745a6c1716bab

commit_message:
HA routers master state now distributed amongst agents

We're currently running with no pre-emption, meaning that
the first router in a cluster to go up will be the master,
regardless of priority. Since the order in which we sent
notifications was constant, the same agent hosted the
master instances of all HA routers, defeating the idea
of load sharing.

Closes-Bug: #1365429
Change-Id: Ia6fe2bd0317c241bf7eb55915df7650dfdc68210

Yes, I agree with Sean.

I would like a test to check that translations, as shipped in the source code, end up being usable. We had a few last-minute release blockers in the past, when someone testing manually two days before release suddenly realized that the shipped translations were actually totally unusable. We even had one case where the release went out with unusable translations. I want to make sure we will never encounter such a case again, so I want some automated test which will detect those issues way before final release week.

It should either be a gate test, or a periodic test with a clear fail escalation procedure, so that we don't miss it.

In summary, before we ask that all projects are translatable, I would like to be reasonably sure that translations won't be lost and won't create as much release havoc as they did in the past..."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-07 13:38:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

For the i18n team, what are the things that i18n support in OpenStack is supposed to do? And then how do we verify that. That seems to include serving horizon in a different language, something with logs, failback when the logs messages aren't there, and possibly user requested language on REST responses (not sure if that got dropped or not).

All of which should be available in some regular place so I can know that translations are working when we cut a milestone. Today it's very much guess work."}, {'account_id': 3108, 'date': '2014-07-09 02:22:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I agree that a translation verification test should be there.

Now the translations cover documents and dashboard. In this release, we could expend our work to user facing messages. Then the translation test will help us to test how openstack running with different characters.

The document translation test could be a maven build to make sure the translated document build is successful. 

Now our translators do the horizon translation test manually. We have a horizon live test website for translators to verify their translations in web UI.

Messages translation are different. Messages translation test could be an integration test with pseudo translation strings. A pseudo translation string could include typical characters from different languages. For example, if we want to verify REST API response message translation, we could run the API tempest test with pseudo translation strings. And we can make this test as a gate test if time is allowed to run tempest test twice: one with English string and one with pseudo translation string.

Regards
Daisy'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-07-09 10:49:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

We definitely also need something that tests log translations are working. We seem to never actually have come to a community consensus over whether logs should be translated here even though this issue has been around for a long time. As this issue keeps coming up it's clear that we never archieved any real consensus.

And I think part of this is because the particular requirement  originated from an IBM product check list. Honestly, I've lost track of how it evolved from there but my last understanding was that there was very mixed support in .cn for this kind of approach. 

So that we don't rehash this *for ever*, maybe now is the time to reach out to Tom at the foundation and see if we can get a pulse of the users in AP on whether this is actually useful and maybe put that part of this discussion to rest."}, {'account_id': 3108, 'date': '2014-08-28 14:09:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I think, the question that this patch is trying to answer is not whether to translate log messages, but whether I18n should be a basic requirement to all projects in the whole community. 

As a software which is used all over the world, I18n is the basic requirement that nobody could say NO. The problem is to which level we support I18n. That's why we are trying to get a community consensus to log translations.

But I don't know why we are trying to get such consensus. The new oslo.i18n lib separate messages. That means, we provide the abilities of I18n, we provide the abilities to localize OpenStack to whatever level people desire. If a company wants to totally localize OpenStack, it could translate all log messages. If a company only wants to localize a part, it could translate a part of log messages or even translate none log messages. 

We could say, OpenStack community, as a global community, provide the abilities to users to localize OpenStack as they want. On the other hand, if we don't provide such abilities, but one user wants, it will be very difficult to add its own localization.

In order to support that, the developers only need to pay attention to the prefixes. Is it not hard for developers, is it?"}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-08-29 09:54:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I agree with Daisy that this change is not about what should or should not be translated, it's about enforcing the ability to do translations if you want to. My -1 on this is more about testing it -- we have had a number of broken solutions in the past that nobody noticed until after release, which is like taking all the work of the translators and not shipping it in the end. I'd like to avoid that by providing proper testing, and I don't feel comfortable asking people to adopt oslo.i18n (therefore triggering new translations) until we've got our stuff in order here."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-09-26 18:41:36.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

clearing my open change queue; we can restore this if someone steps up to lead the work'}]

Further to this, it seems like a really bad idea to me to permit different elements to have a different idea about what the 'glance-registry' service is: I understand and support the need to use a different name on different distributions with vendor packages and all, but having glance think its service is one thing, and some service-monitor package think its another seems like a pretty bad situation to encourage.

I'd really like to see this:
 - compile a single JSON
 - not allow any namespaces or confusion
 - error if conflicting mappings are defined in the image build

That would move the complexity of it all to build time, avoid skew issues biting folk in production, which are my two concerns."}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2014-08-08 13:55:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

lifeless: many of your concerns (checking the mappings to make sure we are duplicating things, etc) came up during the pkg-map review process. I think the decision there was to iterate on these tools and perhaps get to a state where we can verify and check extra things (like not having duplicate service names defined). I'm actually not sure we want to enforce a global namespace (to me these decisions belong within the element). Perhaps these aren't runtime checks but something we could do at test time instead.

Initially though what we are doing here is a very large improvement over the coupling we do today in DIB namely getting rid of the coupling. Furthermore it models exactly how we do things in pkg-map so I see no reason to hold this up for "perfection".

lifeless: I'm not sure I would call our current situation robust in any fashion. I could in fact inline my own distro package name in any element of my choosing. If it isn't the Debian name... well so what, it might not work on Debian but if I land it I'm happy and who cares if you don't use it.

What we are proposing here is a major step forwards already. It encourages users to look around and make a best effort at properly identifying package names for popular distros without the associated coupled DIB change.

As for the global namespace check... well I suppose you could argue that is a feature of the current implementation. I would argue that it just sort of evolved... and that the ownership of these sorts of mappings is really in the elements themselves. 

So I'd like to proceed with this for now and perhaps SPEC out what would happen if we added extra validations to both pkg-map and svc-map in the future with regards to global checks. I'm not actually convinced the extra validations are a good idea so I'd like to try them out in an isolated fashion (i.e. if we do them here, now I may be negative on the approach).

As is I'm +2 on this :)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-08 20:31:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Verified+1

constantly maintain DIB's various bin/map-services files.

commit_message:
Add svc-map element.

Adds a new svc-map element which can be used to install
services based on an in element 'svc-map' YAML config
file format.

This change is intended to decouple elements from DIB
and allow new elements to support multiple distributions
(with various service naming schemes) without having to
constantly maintain DIB's various bin/map-services files.

This patch ensures all of the YAML files are compiled into
a single file without namespaces.  The YAML compilation
process occurs during image creation time and errors if
conflicting mappings are found.

Change-Id: Id11433ea342aace71a358936a7ca3151ec11d506

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-25 02:34:38.000000000', 'message': "Neutron: Atomic update of instance info cache

In the Neutron network API implementation, there is a race condition
between a thread performing periodic task to read and heal instance
network info cache and another thread servicing interface-attach or
interface-detach calls. This patch ensures that instance info cache is
read and then updated in a synchronized block to ensure atomicity.

Please see the bug report for more details.

Conflicts:
        nova/network/base_api.py
        nova/network/neutronv2/api.py
        nova/tests/network/test_neutronv2.py

NOTE(mriedem): Notes on conflicts:

1. base_api didn't exist until Juno so that's where refresh_cache
   lives now.
2. nova.network.neutronv2.api is using oslo.i18n in Juno rather
   than the old gettextutils import.
3. test_neutronv2 didn't start using mock until Juno and the change
   that added the test class is probably something that we won't
   be backporting, so the test class definition is brought back
   with this change for the new test case.

Change-Id: Ifc76f2b1cce834b3c9927359ac9b957bc9f9c65f
Closes-Bug: #1326183
Co-Authored-By: Dan Smith <dansmith@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 232cbfe67ffb7696f115830c711a960af5fa0828)

commit_message:
Neutron: Atomic update of instance info cache

In the Neutron network API implementation, there is a race condition
between a thread performing periodic task to read and heal instance
network info cache and another thread servicing interface-attach or
interface-detach calls. This patch ensures that instance info cache is
read and then updated in a synchronized block to ensure atomicity.

Please see the bug report for more details.

Conflicts:
        nova/network/base_api.py
        nova/network/neutronv2/api.py
        nova/tests/network/test_neutronv2.py

NOTE(mriedem): Notes on conflicts:

1. base_api didn't exist until Juno so that's where refresh_cache
   lives now.
2. nova.network.neutronv2.api is using oslo.i18n in Juno rather
   than the old gettextutils import.
3. test_neutronv2 didn't start using mock until Juno and the change
   that added the test class is probably something that we won't
   be backporting, so the test class definition is brought back
   with this change for the new test case.

Change-Id: Ifc76f2b1cce834b3c9927359ac9b957bc9f9c65f
Closes-Bug: #1326183
Co-Authored-By: Dan Smith <dansmith@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 232cbfe67ffb7696f115830c711a960af5fa0828)

commit_message:
Ensure info cache updates don't overwhelm cells

Cells does its own healing of the info cache outside
of get_instance_nw_info, so we have double healing
happening if info_cache_cells_update is called for every
get_instance_nw_info. This also overwhelms cells'
ability to keep the global db updated at scale. Similar
functionality exists in nova/network/api.py.

Conflicts:
        nova/network/neutronv2/api.py

NOTE(mriedem): This is due to base_api not existing
until Juno, where the refresh_cache decorator now
lives.

Change-Id: I58f681f3674d826e3dce4fa956e2eb0e4c60f82b
(cherry picked from commit 446d433f6fea7624acae371189239a82c94ad455)

Fix error handling

In some cases our code throws Amazon DynamoDB specific
exceptions even we work with REST API.

Also as Armando said - UT would be nice addition.'}, {'account_id': 11784, 'date': '2014-09-11 21:16:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thank you Armando and Jacek for your comments.

In this patch ( https://review.openstack.org/#/c/105611/ )  (Changes to remove the use of mapping tables from Nuage plugin)
the mapping tables in the NuagePlugin were removed.

Before the removal of mapping tables, in the delete router method, the nuage_zone and nuage router mapping was obtained after the deletion of the nuage router. This mapping was present in one of the mapping tables.

After the removal of the mapping tables, iso getting the mapping b/w nuage zone and nuage router, the nuage zone can be obtained directly using the back end function get_zone_by_routerid().
The nuage_zone will not exist if the router is deleted successfully. (The function get_zone_by_routerid() returns None when called from delete_router method as this was called after router delete operation.)

W.r.t adding unit test, as per my understanding and above behavior, the delete_router unit test is performed which tests this Nuage Plugin's delete router method. If the router is deleted successfully, the user and group association will be removed successfully too.

There are supporting functions self.nuageclient.get_usergroup(), self.nuageclient.delete_user() and self.nuageclient.delete_group() already existing in neutron/neutron/tests/unit/nuage/fake_nuageclient.py.

Please let me know if my understanding is correct."}, {'account_id': 11784, 'date': '2014-09-12 19:07:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-12 21:30:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

(1 comment)

If Nuage plugin has proper unit test coverage, this change should have some unit test change because at least mock of nuageclient needs to be removed."}, {'account_id': 11784, 'date': '2014-09-16 20:05:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi Akhiro, As per my understanding, unit tests are isolated, stand-alone tests with no back end (external) dependencies. The reason why we do not need unit test in this case is because this commit fixes a nuage back end related bug.

Now, if the openstack related delete router unit test case which is executed for the nuage delete_router method passes, we can safely assume that the nuage back end code which removes the association of the user and group after router delete will be executed successfully.

Please correct me if my understanding is incorrect.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-09-17 05:42:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I checked nuage plugin test code and it uses the fake client so it looks good in this case. However, We recently use mock approach rather than fake (stub?) approach to check client calls to external system more explicitly.

-1 still exists because of my comment on the summary line of the commit message. The summary line is too generic.'}, {'account_id': 11784, 'date': '2014-09-17 18:43:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-17 20:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Fix to delete user and group association in Nuage Plugin

After a router delete operation, the attached zone to that
router is also deleted. Got rid of code that tried to do
a get operation on the nuage_zone after router delete
operation.
Closes-Bug: #1367864

Change-Id: I01753a472200a961cdcecee703616fd3239abd3c

commit_message:
Remove extraenous instantiations of managers

There were cases where a number of the API managers were being
instantiated more than one time. This could cause a number of
odd edge cases where the managers would have different
configurations and/or different dependency injection results.

The managers should now be properly instantiated only once
unless explicitly required (e.g. testing the token provider
manager raises an exception in badly configured states).

Conflicts:
	keystone/auth/plugins/token.py

Closes-Bug: #1294994
Change-Id: I1babb065065cb5b06899f59568020a1c38f1156c
(cherry-picked from commit 0a1cb0e20247a3c7856b409452b01ad6db8069f0)

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-16 22:36:04.000000000', 'message': 'postgresql: use postgres db instead of template1

In PostgreSQL template1 database is kind of special, as all new databases are
copied from it, when you do CREATE DATABASE. This implies a few restrictions:
e.g. you can't have more than one active session to template1, if one of them
tries to create a database. It will fail with:

    ERROR: source database "template1" is being accessed by other users

Using of postgres database instead of template1 resolves this issue.

Closes-Bug: #1355929

commit_message:
postgresql: use postgres db instead of template1

In PostgreSQL template1 database is kind of special, as all new databases are
copied from it, when you do CREATE DATABASE. This implies a few restrictions:
e.g. you can't have more than one active session to template1, if one of them
tries to create a database. It will fail with:

    ERROR: source database "template1" is being accessed by other users

Using of postgres database instead of template1 resolves this issue.

Closes-Bug: #1355929

Change-Id: I8b1a36163984fbef6be66964456072d32da6a9d0

Our *default* is Ironic, and has been for ages."}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-09-22 21:49:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

AFAIK, the baremetal driver is going to be deleted from the Nova tree as soon as Kilo development opens. So if TripleO needs to maintain support for the baremetal driver, it should do so on the Juno/stable branch, and I think that's reasonably a thing for the TripleO team to decide if they want to support.

Also, I think "sleep(larger N)" is a terrible solution where "sleep(N)" is not good enough. Especially when that's not configurable at all. I would -1 it for that.

This is not solving the problem, but it sounds like it is helping the existing set of users of this code, and it's a trivial change, so I would +1 it for that.

commit_message:
Increase sleeps in baremetal driver

The current sleeps are not long enough in some cases, increasing them
very simply makes the driver far more reliable.

Change-Id: Ida5591f9e4d1eb61e229096d541a8285803efeb5
Closes-Bug: #1316350

commit_message:
Undo changes to obj_make_compatible

Commit 7cdfdccf1bb936d559bd3e247094a817bb3c03f4 attempted to make
the obj_make_compatible calls consistent, but it actually changed
them the wrong way. This fixes them to unwrap nova_object.data
and updates the test that was testing the reverse.

Change-Id: I1a5db4e9817390ba3c2423d33387f780c890de64
Closes-Bug: #1373535

commit_message:
Disable fwaas in neutron server config file

Currently Firewall-as-a-Service isn't used but it is enabled.
It prevents neutron-l3-agent from starting.

Change-Id: I6cc86a30de840108cff91d02bc9002794150f17f
Closes-bug: #1372787

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-25 14:43:53.000000000', 'message': "Update virsh ssh commands to support setting the locale

The patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/124061 in Ironic is changing
the SSH commands to force the commands to use their default language
(whatever language the strings in the application was written in, for
virsh that's english) for output by passing LC_ALL=C as part of the
command line. This is needed because as we do some pattern matchings
with the output of some commands and if the system is configured with
a non-english locale setting the matching is going to fail.

This patch makes the locale variable optional when checking the virsh
commands so it would work with the old and new commands.

Change-Id: I7b6bf0c93c88888231d260036c765228e57b848f
"}]
commit_message:
Update virsh ssh commands to support setting the locale

The patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/124061 in Ironic is changing
the SSH commands to force the commands to use their default language
(whatever language the strings in the application was written in, for
virsh that's english) for output by passing LC_ALL=C as part of the
command line. This is needed because as we do some pattern matchings
with the output of some commands and if the system is configured with
a non-english locale setting the matching is going to fail.

This patch makes the locale variable optional when checking the virsh
commands so it would work with the old and new commands.

Change-Id: I7b6bf0c93c88888231d260036c765228e57b848f

commit_message:
Add a Congress driver for Keystone

This driver uses three keystone API calls to populate Congress tables users,
roles, and tenants.  These are the columns for these three tables:

columns ('username', 'name', enabled', 'tenantId', 'id', 'email').
roles ('id', 'name')
tenants ('enabled', 'description', 'name', 'id')

The keystone driver includes a test.

blueprint: refactor-drivers

Change-Id: I8b77576a72e953971bd99bd7cb0a947bf5dc5aa9

commit_message:
Updates Tempest to match Zaqar's API name change

Zaqar is a messaging service which provides support for different
messaging patterns and messaging related semantics.
This fix changes the old API name -queuing- to a more accurate name, -messaging-.

Change-Id: I63321e8b9f277be040d0f75d5ed9f4461da0defc

commit_message:
Forbid regular users to reset admin-only attrs to default values

A regular user can reset an admin-only attribute to its default
value due to the fact that a corresponding policy rule is
enforced only in the case when an attribute is present in the
target AND has a non-default value.

Added a new attribute "attributes_to_update" which contains a list
of all to-be updated attributes to the body of the target that is
passed to policy.enforce.

Changed a check for whether an attribute is explicitly set.
Now, in the case of update, the function should not pay attention
to a default value of an attribute, but check whether it was
explicitly marked as being updated.

Added unit-tests.

Conflicts:
	neutron/common/constants.py

Closes-Bug: #1357379
Related-Bug: #1338880
Change-Id: I6537bb1da5ef0d6899bc71e4e949f2c760c103c2
(cherry picked from commit 74d10939903984d5f06c1749a8707fa3257e44ff)

USE_SSL could be a very misleading option.

Native SSL is not considered a viable deploymen option by many. Given that the code to do so is available and running it alleviates the need for a slew of stud processes I went ahead and implemented it. That said, the OSSG promotes the use of TLS proxy over native SSL so we may want to encourage that as a use case over native.

Enabling SSL via the proxy is as easy as adding a single server to the enabled list.

Enabling native SSL is purposefully more difficult. I can certainly change it to use the same cert/key/CA file everywhere but I was keeping with the model that Jamie set out. I'd want to rip that out completely if we go with a single-cert solution. It would also be fairly trivial to execute the same CA-creation calls that the TLS Proxy code already uses.

I'd like some feedback before I start ripping out code."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-06-17 15:45:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'd certainly prefer to use the existing CA bits everywhere.  If there is a shortcoming in that let's fix it rather than do something else.

The continued value of native SSL in the servers is not obvious to me.  They are not consistent in support or configuration, nor do I believe an actual production deployment of OpenStack will use it.  I'd like to know there is actual value in spending testing resources on that before committing to it.

I think we're better off using a proxy or running WSGI under Apache to get SSL, and honestly, if we could do that with Apache the value of the stud proxy implementation goes down..."}, {'account_id': 7662, 'date': '2014-06-17 16:00:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The native SSL configuration code isn't a whole lot different than the TLS Proxy code so IMHO it won't be a testing burden. There are actually uses doing native SSL in production now (for good or bad).

The OSSG promotes the use of TLS proxies for more than just avoiding python SSL (load balancing and such). I'm not set on stud as the proxy, just tried to keep the changes as limited as possible. The tls-proxy part is abstracted well enough that changing the actual proxy should be a no-brainer."}, {'account_id': 7662, 'date': '2014-06-19 14:57:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-19 14:57:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

The grenade tests are failing because they call into the devstack library functions directly without doing similar setup to stack.sh, notably it doesn't set SERVICE_PROTOCOL.

My previous attempt at working around this was disliked by Sean.

I see two solutions, both of which involve the same line of code, it is just a matter of placement:

SERVICE_PROTOCOL=${SERVICE_PROTOCOL:-http}

1. File a bug against grenade to add this
2. Add it at the top of lib/nova

It is really a question of what devstack modules can assume is set by stack.sh and what they can't.

I prefer #1"}, {'account_id': 7662, 'date': '2014-07-29 20:26:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-29 20:27:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

[{'created': '2014-06-09 18:51:07.000000000', 'message': 'Configure endpoints to use SSL natively or via proxy

Configure nova, cinder and glance to use SSL on the endpoints using
either SSL natively or via a TLS proxy using stud.

This adds some limited support for neutron using native SSL.

To enable SSL via proxy, in local.conf add

ENABLED_SERVICES+=,tls-proxy

This will create a new test root CA, a subordinate CA and an SSL
server cert. It uses the value of hostname -f for the certificate
subject. The CA certicates are also added to the system CA bundle.

To enable SSL natively, in local.conf add:

SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES="<services>"

Where services is one or more of key, nova, cinder and glance.

Native SSL requires the user to provide their own SSL certificate,
private key and CA for the service. The same set can be used for
multiple services. Each service requires these lines in local.conf:

<SERVICE>_SSL_CERT=/path/to/cert
<SERVICE>_SSL_KEY=/path/to/key
<SERVICE>_SSL_PATH=/path/to/ca

You should also set SERVICE_HOST to the FQDN of the host. This
value defaults to the host IP address.

Change-Id: I36fe56c063ca921131ad98439bd452cb135916ac
Closes-Bug: 1328226
'}, {'created': '2014-06-10 14:22:48.000000000', 'message': 'Configure endpoints to use SSL natively or via proxy

Configure nova, cinder and glance to use SSL on the endpoints using
either SSL natively or via a TLS proxy using stud.

This adds some limited support for neutron using native SSL.

To enable SSL via proxy, in local.conf add

ENABLED_SERVICES+=,tls-proxy

This will create a new test root CA, a subordinate CA and an SSL
server cert. It uses the value of hostname -f for the certificate
subject. The CA certicates are also added to the system CA bundle.

To enable SSL natively, in local.conf add:

SSL_ENABLED_SERVICES="<services>"

Where services is one or more of key, nova, cinder and glance.

Native SSL requires the user to provide their own SSL certificate,
private key and CA for the service. The same set can be used for
multiple services. Each service requires these lines in local.conf:

<SERVICE>_SSL_CERT=/path/to/cert
<SERVICE>_SSL_KEY=/path/to/key
<SERVICE>_SSL_PATH=/path/to/ca

You should also set SERVICE_HOST to the FQDN of the host. This
value defaults to the host IP address.

Change-Id: I36fe56c063ca921131ad98439bd452cb135916ac

commit_message:
Configure endpoints to use SSL natively or via proxy

Configure nova, cinder, glance, swift and neutron to use SSL
on the endpoints using either SSL natively or via a TLS proxy
using stud.

To enable SSL via proxy, in local.conf add

ENABLED_SERVICES+=,tls-proxy

This will create a new test root CA, a subordinate CA and an SSL
server cert. It uses the value of hostname -f for the certificate
subject. The CA certicates are also added to the system CA bundle.

To enable SSL natively, in local.conf add:

USE_SSL=True

Native SSL by default will also use the devstack-generate root and
subordinate CA.

You can override this on a per-service basis by setting

<SERVICE>_SSL_CERT=/path/to/cert
<SERVICE>_SSL_KEY=/path/to/key
<SERVICE>_SSL_PATH=/path/to/ca

You should also set SERVICE_HOST to the FQDN of the host. This
value defaults to the host IP address.

Change-Id: I36fe56c063ca921131ad98439bd452cb135916ac
Closes-Bug: 1328226

there are OS_* variables set in the environment. There
is already code in the test setUp to remove ST_* variables,
so we should do the same for OS_* variables.

then restore any unwanted variables found in os.environ.

The existing setUp() takes a copy of os.environ and then
deletes any ST_* variables in the original. In tearDown() it

commit_message:
Fix unit tests failing when OS_ env vars are set

tests/unit/test_shell.py:TestParsing tests can fail if
there are OS_* variables set in the environment. There
is already code in the test setUp to remove ST_* variables,
so we should do the same for OS_* variables.

This patch also changes the mechanism used to remove and
then restore any unwanted variables found in os.environ.

The existing setUp() takes a copy of os.environ and then
deletes any ST_* variables in the original. In tearDown() it
sets os.environ as the copy. However, the environ imported
into shell.py remains pointing to the original os.environ
object. So after the first call to tearDown, subsequent
mocking of os.environ has no effect on shell.environ.
This renders some of the tests ineffective e.g.
test_insufficient_env_vars_v3 is not actually setting any
vars in shell.environ.

The issue can be provoked by repeating a test:
nosetests -w tests/unit/ test_shell.py:TestParsing.test_args_v3 \
 test_shell.py:TestParsing.test_args_v3

The test will pass first time and fail second time.

Change-Id: I5d100f81115e74878d510326acb5777e6a3626c8

So, this was inspired by Michael Barton's sendfile patch (https://review.openstack.org/82186). It's a bit more complicated, but it keeps the MD5 check and quarantine working, which you can't do with plain sendfile().

Oh, and for reference, splicetee.splice() and splicetee.tee() *do* release the GIL, so calling them from within a threadpool actually helps. :) Check out the splicetee source; it's only a couple hundred lines of C, and it's very readable."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-25 20:05:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Fixed some parameter ordering: turns out IOError() wants (errno, message), not (message, errno). That's why the tests were failing on the 2.6 testrunners; they've got an older kernel, and so Swift couldn't get MD5 sockets, but I had the parameter order backwards, and "Failed to initialize MD5 socket" never equals errno.EAFNOSUPPORT :)

[{'created': '2014-06-25 19:03:25.000000000', 'message': 'Zero-copy object-server GET responses with splice()

This commit lets the object server use splice() and tee() to move data
from disk to the network without ever copying it into user space.

Requires the "splicetee" library and Linux. Sorry, FreeBSD folks. You
still have the old mechanism, as does anyone who doesn't want to
install splicetee. It's optional. (While I normally dislike optional
dependencies, this one requires a particular OS, so it can't be
mandatory).

Note that this only applies to GET responses without Range headers. It
can easily be extended to single-range GET requests, but this commit
leaves that for future work. Same goes for PUT requests, or at least
non-chunked ones.

This requires a relatively recent kernel (2.6.38+) to work, which
includes the two most recent Ubuntu LTS releases (Precise and Trusty)
as well as RHEL 7. However, it excludes Lucid and RHEL 6. On those
systems, setting "splice = on" will result in warnings in the logs but
no actual use of splice.

Also fixed a long-standing annoyance in FakeLogger:

    >>> fake_logger.warn('stuff')
    >>> fake_logger.get_lines_for_level('warn')
    []
    >>>

This, of course, is because the correct log level is 'warning'. Now
you get a KeyError if you call get_lines_for_level with a bogus log
level.

Change-Id: Ic6d6b833a5b04ca2019be94b1b90d941929d21c8

This commit lets the object server use splice() and tee() to move data
from disk to the network without ever copying it into user space.

Requires Linux. Sorry, FreeBSD folks. You still have the old
mechanism, as does anyone who doesn't want to use splice. This
requires a relatively recent kernel (2.6.38+) to work, which includes
the two most recent Ubuntu LTS releases (Precise and Trusty) as well
as RHEL 7. However, it excludes Lucid and RHEL 6. On those systems,
setting "splice = on" will result in warnings in the logs but no
actual use of splice.

Note that this only applies to GET responses without Range headers. It
can easily be extended to single-range GET requests, but this commit
leaves that for future work. Same goes for PUT requests, or at least
non-chunked ones.

On some real hardware I had laying around (not a VM), this produced a
37% reduction in CPU usage for GETs made directly to the object
server. Measurements were done by looking at /proc/<pid>/stat,
specifically the utime and stime fields (user and kernel CPU jiffies,
respectively).

Note: There is a Python module called "splicetee" available on PyPi,
but it's licensed under the GPL, so it cannot easily be added to
OpenStack's requirements. That's why this patch uses ctypes instead.

Also fixed a long-standing annoyance in FakeLogger:

    >>> fake_logger.warn('stuff')
    >>> fake_logger.get_lines_for_level('warn')
    []
    >>>

This, of course, is because the correct log level is 'warning'. Now
you get a KeyError if you call get_lines_for_level with a bogus log
level.

but it's licensed under the GPL, so it cannot easily be added to

commit_message:
Zero-copy object-server GET responses with splice()

This commit lets the object server use splice() and tee() to move data
from disk to the network without ever copying it into user space.

Requires Linux. Sorry, FreeBSD folks. You still have the old
mechanism, as does anyone who doesn't want to use splice. This
requires a relatively recent kernel (2.6.38+) to work, which includes
the two most recent Ubuntu LTS releases (Precise and Trusty) as well
as RHEL 7. However, it excludes Lucid and RHEL 6. On those systems,
setting "splice = on" will result in warnings in the logs but no
actual use of splice.

Note that this only applies to GET responses without Range headers. It
can easily be extended to single-range GET requests, but this commit
leaves that for future work. Same goes for PUT requests, or at least
non-chunked ones.

On some real hardware I had laying around (not a VM), this produced a
37% reduction in CPU usage for GETs made directly to the object
server. Measurements were done by looking at /proc/<pid>/stat,
specifically the utime and stime fields (user and kernel CPU jiffies,
respectively).

Note: There is a Python module called "splicetee" available on PyPi,
but it's licensed under the GPL, so it cannot easily be added to
OpenStack's requirements. That's why this patch uses ctypes instead.

Also fixed a long-standing annoyance in FakeLogger:

    >>> fake_logger.warn('stuff')
    >>> fake_logger.get_lines_for_level('warn')
    []
    >>>

This, of course, is because the correct log level is 'warning'. Now
you get a KeyError if you call get_lines_for_level with a bogus log
level.

Change-Id: Ic6d6b833a5b04ca2019be94b1b90d941929d21c8

commit_message:
Adds RBAC to Keystone V2 API get_endpoints method.

Added the @controller.protected() decorator to the get_endpoints
method so that the permissions for accessing this method are taken
from the policy.json file.
Removed the hardcoded admin-only permissions.

Change-Id: I99db0ae7a6dea8d6bc32f6ed3af758ae0dcc5e18
Closes-Bug: 1350879

I just ran tests and here are the results (not looking good):

With this code, the memcached server stopping and restarting will cause a deadlock in keystone. The only way to recover is to restart keystone (or apache if keystone is under apache).

The thread.local seems to be *required* or we need better detection of dead memcache clients.

Prior to this code a restart of memcached may cause active requests to hang but subsequent requests will work as new memcache clients are added.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-09-07 18:50:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

This deadlock-feel might be related to the defaults for socket_timeout, dead_retry etc.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-09-07 18:52:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Sorry about the comment spam, hit publish without the second sentence on the last one. In that case the defaults need to be fixed to be sane and work much more similarly to our current implementation so a restart of memcached can be mostly non-disruptive (barring the loss of the data in memcached).'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-09-07 18:58:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2014-09-07 19:25:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

The deadlock you are getting is really strange. I've tested this pool before posting by running Keystone (devstack, non-Apache) with 3 local memcached servers. I've "kill -STOP"ed some of them, -CONT'ed afterwards, and never got any problems other than small slowdown after STOPping a server (socket timeout waiting). We've also did thorough testing of the same code for Icehouse (under big load, with small load, shutting down one of nodes with memcached, etc).

Can you provide more details on what your test env is and how can I reproduce deadlock?

I'll address all comments tomorrow and will move pool to keystonemiddleware so that we'll land it where it belongs without need to move it around.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-09-08 01:24:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

The deadlock is apparently part of the way the clients are reaped and how servers are marked as dead.

In the case that you need to restart the memcache cluster (or single server if you only have one), leaving a complete interruption (not just a stop/cont, full cycle), which I assume would be the same result as a complete loss of connectivity to the memcache server, you get this hang. It looks like it might be strictly related to the dead_retry. If the memcache server is marked as dead (all of them) you end up having to wait for 300 seconds for it to recover.

I would argue that if all servers are marked as dead, this "dead" retry needs a special case to avoid more serious interruptions to service.

This was produced on a clean devstack with a single memcache server as well as on a devstack with multiple memcache servers running. The toekn backend was set to be Memcache.

So I correct myself, this isn't a deadlock, but it is a complete interruption in service until the servers are retried in ~5min.'}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2014-09-08 05:29:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Oh, right. All dead is the case I've overlooked. WIll add a clause for it in acquire/release."}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2014-09-09 11:01:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-09 12:16:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

[{'created': '2014-09-05 19:36:26.000000000', 'message': "Add a pool of memcached clients

This would avoid creation of too many connections and keep 'dead' flags
on memcached servers

To use it, set 'keystone.cache.memcache_pool' as active dogpile.cache
backend:

[cache]
backend=keystone.cache.memcache_pool
backend_argument=url:127.0.0.1:11211
backend_argument=memcache_dead_retry:300
backend_argument=memcache_socket_timeout:3
backend_argument=pool_maxsize:10
backend_argument=pool_unused_timeout:60
backend_argument=pool_debug:

Where:
- url - comma-separated list of host:port pairs (was already there);
- memcache_dead_retry - number of seconds memcached server is considered
  dead before its tried again;
- memcache_socket_timeout - timeout in seconds for every call to a
  server;
- pool_maxsize - max total number of open connections in the pool;
- pool_unused_timeout - number of seconds a connection is held unused in
  the pool before its closed;
- pool_debug - add non-empty string if you want debug log of this pool
  (there are a lot of logs there).

NOTE: there is no way to specify these parameters for token backend
without this patch: https://gerrit.mirantis.com/20587

Closes-bug: #1332058
Closes-bug: #1360446
Change-Id: I3544894482b30a47fcd4fac8948d03136fd83f14

"}, {'created': '2014-09-11 11:19:52.000000000', 'message': "Add a pool of memcached clients

This would avoid creation of too many connections and keep 'dead' flags
on memcached servers.

The core module that provides pool functionality is copied between
keystone and keystonemiddleware (see _memcache_pool.py in this change
https://review.openstack.org/119774 in keystonemiddleware).

This backend is used instead of dogpile's backend in memcache token
persistence backend, to configure it one should use following config
arguments:

[memcache]
servers = 127.0.0.1:11211
dead_retry = 300
socket_timeout = 3
pool_maxsize = 10
pool_unused_timeout = 60
pool_debug = False

Where:
- servers - comma-separated list of host:port pairs (was already there);
- memcache_dead_retry - number of seconds memcached server is considered
  dead before its tried again;
- memcache_socket_timeout - timeout in seconds for every call to a
  server;
- pool_maxsize - max total number of open connections in the pool;
- pool_unused_timeout - number of seconds a connection is held unused in
  the pool before its closed;
- pool_debug - add non-empty string if you want debug log of this pool
  (there are a lot of logs there).

To use it as cache backend, set 'keystone.cache.memcache_pool' as active
dogpile.cache backend, other options are the same, but with 'memcache_'
prefix:

[cache]
backend = keystone.cache.memcache_pool
memcache_servers = 127.0.0.1:11211
memcache_dead_retry = 300
memcache_socket_timeout = 3
memcache_pool_maxsize = 10
memcache_pool_unused_timeout = 60
memcache_pool_debug = False

Closes-bug: #1332058
Closes-bug: #1360446
Change-Id: I3544894482b30a47fcd4fac8948d03136fd83f14

"}, {'created': '2014-09-16 02:37:05.000000000', 'message': "Add a pool of memcached clients

This patchset adds a pool of memcache clients. This pool allows for reuse of
a client object, prevents too many client object from being instantiated, and
maintains proper tracking of dead servers so as to limit delays
when a server (or all servers) become unavailable.

The new memcache pool backend is used instead of dogpile's default memcache
backend in the memcache token persistence driver. To configure the new backend
one should use following config arguments:

[memcache]
servers = 127.0.0.1:11211
dead_retry = 300
socket_timeout = 3
pool_maxsize = 10
pool_unused_timeout = 60

Where:
- servers - comma-separated list of host:port pairs (was already there);
- dead_retry - number of seconds memcached server is considered dead
  before it is tried again;
- socket_timeout - timeout in seconds for every call to a server;
- pool_maxsize - max total number of open connections in the pool;
- pool_unused_timeout - number of seconds a connection is held unused in
  the pool before it is closed;

The new memcache pool backend can be used as the driver for the Keystone
caching layer. To use it as caching driver, set
'keystone.cache.memcache_pool' as the value of the [cache]\backend option,
the other options are the same as above, but with 'memcache_' prefix:

[cache]
backend = keystone.cache.memcache_pool
memcache_servers = 127.0.0.1:11211
memcache_dead_retry = 300
memcache_socket_timeout = 3
memcache_pool_maxsize = 10
memcache_pool_unused_timeout = 60

Co-Authored-By: Morgan Fainberg <morgan.fainberg@gmail.com>
Closes-bug: #1332058
Closes-bug: #1360446
Change-Id: I3544894482b30a47fcd4fac8948d03136fd83f14

- dead_retry - number of seconds memcached server is considered dead
  before it is tried again;
- socket_timeout - timeout in seconds for every call to a server;
- pool_maxsize - max total number of open connections in the pool;
- pool_unused_timeout - number of seconds a connection is held unused in
  the pool before it is closed;

The new memcache pool backend can be used as the driver for the Keystone
caching layer. To use it as caching driver, set
'keystone.cache.memcache_pool' as the value of the [cache]\backend option,
the other options are the same as above, but with 'memcache_' prefix:

[cache]
backend = keystone.cache.memcache_pool
memcache_servers = 127.0.0.1:11211
memcache_dead_retry = 300
memcache_socket_timeout = 3
memcache_pool_maxsize = 10
memcache_pool_unused_timeout = 60

commit_message:
Add a pool of memcached clients

This patchset adds a pool of memcache clients. This pool allows for reuse of
a client object, prevents too many client object from being instantiated, and
maintains proper tracking of dead servers so as to limit delays
when a server (or all servers) become unavailable.

The new memcache pool backend is available either by being set as the memcache
backend or by using keystone.token.persistence.backends.memcache_pool.Token for
the Token memcache persistence driver.

[memcache]
servers = 127.0.0.1:11211
dead_retry = 300
socket_timeout = 3
pool_maxsize = 10
pool_unused_timeout = 60

Where:
- servers - comma-separated list of host:port pairs (was already there);
- dead_retry - number of seconds memcached server is considered dead
  before it is tried again;
- socket_timeout - timeout in seconds for every call to a server;
- pool_maxsize - max total number of open connections in the pool;
- pool_unused_timeout - number of seconds a connection is held unused in
  the pool before it is closed;

The new memcache pool backend can be used as the driver for the Keystone
caching layer. To use it as caching driver, set
'keystone.cache.memcache_pool' as the value of the [cache]\backend option,
the other options are the same as above, but with 'memcache_' prefix:

[cache]
backend = keystone.cache.memcache_pool
memcache_servers = 127.0.0.1:11211
memcache_dead_retry = 300
memcache_socket_timeout = 3
memcache_pool_maxsize = 10
memcache_pool_unused_timeout = 60

Co-Authored-By: Morgan Fainberg <morgan.fainberg@gmail.com>
Closes-bug: #1332058
Closes-bug: #1360446
Change-Id: I3544894482b30a47fcd4fac8948d03136fd83f14

commit_message:
Add validation to Resource Usage daily report

The limit project count field doesn't have any validation and
currently fails if the value supplied can't be cast by
python to an int, or if the value is 0.

Solution is to add some jQuery based validation to make sure
that field contains nothing but digits, and is non-zero.  Also
change the field to numeric type so modern browsers will handle
it better.

Change-Id: I47688c2342b8ce6c1e7728f53111d8f4ce6bb98e
Closes-bug: #1288512

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-26 01:44:00.000000000', 'message': 'Add expected status for all HEAD requests in tests

We recently had some inconsistencies between responses for GET and HEAD
methods for calls that support both methods. This inconsistency was made
obvious when deploying Keystone in httpd since HEAD requests are converted
to GET requests. In order to ensure that our reponse status is correct for
HEAD calls, we should check the status in our tests.

This patch adds expected status checks for all HEAD requests that were
not previously checked.
Related-bug: #1334368

Change-Id: Ifa66500249e9d2426cde19667d092b36a8855337
'}]
commit_message:
Add expected status for all HEAD requests in tests

We recently had some inconsistencies between responses for GET and HEAD
methods for calls that support both methods. This inconsistency was made
obvious when deploying Keystone in httpd since HEAD requests are converted
to GET requests. In order to ensure that our reponse status is correct for
HEAD calls, we should check the status in our tests.

This patch adds expected status checks for all HEAD requests that were
not previously checked.
Related-bug: #1334368

Change-Id: Ifa66500249e9d2426cde19667d092b36a8855337

commit_message:
Add database users for instances.

Create, List, and Delete operations are supported. Because the
password is write-on-create only and otherwise omitted, this property
is fully implemented. Create is reimplemented to format as a list,
expected by the service.

Change-Id: Id8b09ea7863d402ccda5b33ad947cd54344cf85b

commit_message:
Fixes stealing of agent responses in some cases

When deployment of environment fails with exception AgentListener.stop() is not
called and thus there remains a listener for RabbitMQ response queue.
Besides being a resource leak it introduces another problems: when that environment
get redeployed it becomes 2 listeners on the same queue and responses from agents
may be stolen by zombie listener making workflow wait forever or response
(hang deployment)

Change-Id: Ic4cedd323ab7b55690d095ed8addcb0dc3e335a7
Closes-Bug: #1369589

commit_message:
labs: reorder setup_neutron_network.sh

This patch reorders the content of setup_neutron_network.sh to more
closely match the order of instructions in the install-guide, making it
easier to compare script and instructions.

Change-Id: Ifa5e23b3d9b0af321b907ab75bd62b171555750b
Co-Authored-By: Pranav Salunke <dguitarbite@gmail.com>

commit_message:
libvirt: Use VIR_DOMAIN_AFFECT_LIVE for paused instances

When a volume is attached to a paused instance, it does not
appear in the instance's block devices list (i.e. lsblk)
after the instance has resumed. A similar situation
happens when detaching a volume from a paused instance; the
block device continues to exists in the block devices list,
where it should not.  It was found that the volume is only
persisted in the domain's config settings and not its active
settings, since only the VIR_DOMAIN_AFFECT_CONFIG flag was used
on attach and detach volume.  In order to affect the active
settings, the VIR_DOMAIN_AFFECT_LIVE flag has to be added when
attaching and detaching volumes.

This change adjusts little about the unit test:
add two imports.

Change-Id: I9c90a410a7ecb91f5a4de28acee21fe7da49242c
Closes-Bug: #1242366
Related-Bug: #1299331
(cherry picked from commit ead9cfca93c9b5ca55e3ba269213c98d5e6e1d38)

commit_message:
Consider allowed cpus in numa placement

The current implementation of the libvirt driver's NUMA cpuset
placement does not take into account conf defined vcpu
pin set. As a result, the conf may define a subset of vcpus
applicable to NUMA, but the cell (node) selection logic
may not properly pin an instance to a cell as defined by
the vcpu pin set.

This patch updates the libvirt NUMA node selection logic
to incorporate the vcpu pin set such that a cell is properly
selected based on the conf value (if provided). Additionally
this patch adds a unit test to verify the pinning placement.

Change-Id: I7f3afe0e56da97e841c96c143ff6dececa77f7b7
Closes-Bug: 1372845

commit_message:
Don't call provision.py directly

When testr.conf calls the sqlalchemy/provision.py script directly,
sys.path[0] is the directory that invoked the script.  So when it
tries to import openstack.common.db you end up with an import failure.

---
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "./openstack/common/db/sqlalchemy/provision.py", line 27, in <module>
    from openstack.common.db import exception as exc
ImportError: No module named openstack.common.db
---

The solution is to run it with -m

Closes-Bug: #1303579
Change-Id: Ia7ff187df1685f0dd5ef32c3f6de474218874b04
(cherry picked from commit 2ae2377b)

commit_message:
Remove unused command in tox.ini

patch_tox_venv.py is not found in this project,
so 'tox -ecover' command report error. This fixes it.

Change-Id: I415f305f7eb98e444b4f6b340409bc5d32d4e9bb

What name will the new group have?'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2014-08-25 15:55:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

That's a good question.  We can't have . in the group name, right?  So it would have to be something like oslo-concurrency or oslo_concurrency.  Not sure we want to go just concurrency since that could reasonably conflict with something else.

Looking at a few existing sample configs, it looks like _ is the accepted separator, so I think that probably makes the most sense.

I suppose we could just go with "lockutils" in this case too.  That actually might be a little cleaner as a user-facing name.  There's no real reason we need to expose the fact that these options are coming from an oslo lib.

Anybody else have a preference?'}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2014-08-25 16:01:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Ben, oslo.messaging does not seem to be using any group.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-09-26 13:58:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:
